canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81894","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81894"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA parent presents to the General Practice clinic seeking dietary advice regarding her eight-month-old son. Her older child has a peanut allergy, developing urticaria and facial swelling with exposure. She has avoided giving peanut-containing foods to her younger son due to concerns about potential allergic reactions. The infant has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, her son appears well with vital signs within normal limits. He is growing appropriately for age and has no rashes or other concerning findings.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gradually introduce smooth peanut butter at home","Avoid peanut-containing foods until age two years","Complete a three-month course of probiotics before introducing peanuts","Supervise first peanut exposure in the clinic","Prescribe adrenaline autoinjector before introducing peanuts"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case addresses the introduction of allergenic foods in infants with family history of food allergy. Current evidence, particularly from the LEAP (Learning Early About Peanut Allergy) study, strongly supports early introduction of allergenic foods, including peanuts, between 4-12 months of age. This approach has been shown to significantly reduce the risk of developing food allergies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGradually introduce smooth peanut butter at home\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate approach. Small amounts (1/4 teaspoon) should be introduced initially and increased gradually if tolerated. Regular inclusion in the diet should continue if no reaction occurs, as irregular exposure may increase allergy risk. The first exposure should occur when the infant is well and can be observed for 2 hours afterwards.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAvoid peanut-containing foods until age two years\u003C/strong\u003E is outdated advice that was common in the 1990s and early 2000s. Delaying introduction may actually increase the risk of developing food allergy. Multiple studies have now demonstrated that early introduction during the window of immune tolerance is protective.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete a three-month course of probiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is not evidence-based for primary prevention of food allergy. While probiotics are being studied for various immune conditions and treatment of established allergies, they are not recommended for preventing food allergy development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESupervise first peanut exposure in the clinic\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary for infants with no personal history of allergic reaction. Medical supervision during first exposure is only recommended for infants with severe eczema or egg allergy, as these are the highest risk factors for peanut allergy. Having a sibling with peanut allergy increases risk but does not warrant supervised introduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrescribe adrenaline autoinjector\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as there is no history of previous allergic reaction. Adrenaline autoinjectors are prescribed for patients with diagnosed food allergy at risk of anaphylaxis, not as a preventive measure during initial introduction of foods.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["All infants should be given allergenic foods including peanuts within the first year of life, even those at high risk of allergy, as early introduction reduces allergy risk.","Having a sibling with food allergy increases risk but is not a contraindication to introducing allergenic foods - only severe eczema or egg allergy warrant supervised introduction.","Smooth peanut butter should be introduced gradually at home starting with small amounts, with regular inclusion in diet if tolerated to maintain tolerance."],"references":["ASCIA contributors, 2020. ASCIA Guidelines - Infant Feeding and Allergy Prevention. Australiasian society of clinical immunology and allergy. Access at: https://www.allergy.org.au/hp/papers/infant-feeding-and-allergy-prevention.","Chebar Lozinsky A, Loke P, Orsini F, O\u0027Sullivan M, L Prescott S, Gold MS, Quinn P, DunnGalvin A, Lk Tang M, PPOIT study team. Study protocol of a multicentre, randomised, controlled trial evaluating the effectiveness of probiotic and peanut oral immunotherapy (PPOIT) in inducing desensitisation or tolerance in children with peanut allergy compared with oral immunotherapy (OIT) alone and with placebo (the PPOIT-003 study). BMJ Open 10 (9) : e035871(2020) PubMed (Grant IDs: GNT1105429, APP1134812)","Greenhawt M. The Learning Early About Peanut Allergy Study: The Benefits of Early Peanut Introduction, and a New Horizon in Fighting the Food Allergy Epidemic. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2015;62(6):1509-1521. doi:10.1016/j.pcl.2015.07.010"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67171"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2465"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67171","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67171"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-27T11:58:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-27T11:59:22+10:30","number":6,"notes":"MB reviewed stale item - updated references, reset review window.","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-27T11:58:27+10:30","plagiarismScore":19.6,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-2465-6.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2